<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much dirt do I need to remove?", answer: "Multiply length × width × depth for a rectangular pit to get cubic feet, then divide by 27 to get cubic yards. For a circular hole, use π × radius² × depth. The calculator does this automatically and also applies a soil swell factor to estimate the loose volume you will actually haul away." },
  { question: "What is the swell factor for soil?", answer: "When soil is excavated, it bulks up because the grains lose their compacted arrangement. Typical swell factors are: dry sand 12%, loam 25%, clay 30-40%, hard rock 50-65%. A 25% swell is a safe default for mixed residential soil. Multiply bank cubic yards by (1 + swell%) to get loose cubic yards — the volume your dump truck actually hauls." },
  { question: "How many cubic yards fit in a dump truck?", answer: "A standard 10-wheeler dump truck hauls about 10 cubic yards of loose dirt. Smaller tri-axle trucks carry 14 to 16 cubic yards, and large semi-trailer dumps haul 20 to 25 cubic yards. The calculator defaults to 10 cubic yards per load so you can size your hauling contract conservatively." },
  { question: "How deep should a basement foundation be?", answer: "Basement excavation typically goes 8 to 9 feet below grade, plus a foot of over-dig for forms and waterproofing. Crawl space foundations are 3 to 4 feet deep. In freezing climates, footings must reach below the local frost line — 42 to 48 inches in the northern US, 12 inches or less in the Deep South." },
  { question: "Do I need a permit to excavate?", answer: "Most residential excavation for foundations, pools, and septic systems requires a building permit. Call 811 (Dig Safe) at least three business days before digging to have underground utilities marked for free — it is the law in every US state and failure to call can cost thousands in repair fees and delay your project." }
]) %>

